// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// TOPIC SUMMARIES (4-6 sentences each)
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

const SUMMARIES: Record<string, string> = {
  "Living in a digital world": "The digital world describes how computers and the internet have changed nearly every part of modern life, from how we communicate to how we shop and work. Digital devices process information as binary data - sequences of 0s and 1s. The internet connects billions of devices globally, enabling instant sharing of information. Digital technology continues to evolve rapidly, creating both opportunities and challenges for society. Understanding the basics of how digital systems work helps us use them more effectively and safely.",
  "The evolving computer": "Computers have changed dramatically since the first electronic machines in the 1940s. Early computers used vacuum tubes and filled entire rooms, but transistors made computers smaller and more reliable in the late 1950s. Integrated circuits packed thousands of transistors onto a single chip, enabling personal computers in the 1970s. Today's microprocessors contain billions of transistors and fit in your pocket. Each generation brought improvements in speed, size, cost, and energy efficiency.",
  "Digital media": "Digital media refers to audio, images, and video stored as numbers rather than as physical patterns. To create a digital image, the brightness and colour of each tiny dot (pixel) is measured and stored as a number. For audio, the volume (amplitude) of sound is measured thousands of times per second - a process called sampling. The number of bits used to store each measurement is called bit depth, and more bits mean better quality. Digital files can be copied, transmitted, and edited without any loss of quality.",
  "A world built of data": "Data is the raw material of the digital world - numbers, text, images, and everything else stored on computers. Databases organise data into structured tables so it can be efficiently stored, searched, and updated. A primary key uniquely identifies each record in a table. SQL (Structured Query Language) is used to query and manipulate relational databases. Binary is the fundamental number system computers use, representing all data as sequences of 0s and 1s.",
  "Weaving the web": "The World Wide Web is a collection of documents and resources linked together using hyperlinks and accessible via the internet. Web pages are written in HTML (HyperText Markup Language), which defines structure and content. CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) controls how pages look, and JavaScript adds interactivity. A web browser requests pages from web servers using the HTTP protocol. URLs (Uniform Resource Locators) are the addresses of web resources.",
  "Crossing boundaries - HCI and design": "Human Computer Interaction (HCI) is the study of how people interact with technology and how to design systems that are easy and enjoyable to use. Good interface design follows principles such as consistency, feedback, and error prevention. Usability means how easily users can accomplish their goals with a system. Accessibility means designing systems that can be used by people with a wide range of abilities and disabilities. Jakob Nielsen's 10 usability heuristics are widely used guidelines for evaluating interface designs.",
  "Programming with Scratch - sequences and sprites": "Scratch is a visual programming language designed to teach programming concepts without typing code. Programs are built by connecting colourful blocks that snap together. A sprite is an object that can move and perform actions on the stage. Sequences are the most basic programming concept - instructions executed one after another in order. Scripts in Scratch start with event blocks like 'when green flag clicked'. Learning to sequence instructions correctly is the foundation of all programming.",
  "Numbers, strings and lists": "Variables are named storage locations that hold values which can change as a program runs. Numbers allow mathematical operations like addition, subtraction, and multiplication. Strings are sequences of characters (text) that can be joined together - this is called concatenation. Lists store multiple values in a single variable, accessed by their position (index). In Scratch, you can create variables and lists from the Variables blocks category.",
  "Selection and Booleans": "Selection allows programs to make decisions by checking conditions and executing different code depending on the result. An if-then block runs code only when a condition is true. An if-then-else block runs one set of code when true and a different set when false. Boolean values can only be true or false. Comparison operators like greater than, less than, and equals to produce Boolean results. Complex conditions can be built using 'and', 'or', and 'not' operators.",
  "Loops": "Loops allow a block of code to be repeated multiple times without having to copy it out. A count-controlled loop (like 'repeat 10') repeats a fixed number of times. A condition-controlled loop (like 'repeat until') keeps repeating until a condition becomes true. A 'forever' loop repeats indefinitely and never stops on its own. Loops save time and make code much shorter and easier to read. Nested loops are loops inside other loops, used for patterns and grids.",
  "Nested structures and modularity": "Modularity means breaking a large program into smaller, self-contained pieces. In Scratch, custom blocks (My Blocks) work like functions - you define them once and use them anywhere. Nesting means placing one structure inside another, such as an if statement inside a loop. Well-structured programs are easier to read, test, and update. Decomposition is the skill of breaking a complex problem down into smaller sub-problems, each of which can be solved separately.",
  "Algorithms and sorting": "An algorithm is a precise, step-by-step set of instructions for solving a problem. Good algorithms are efficient - they solve problems using as few steps as possible. Bubble sort repeatedly compares adjacent items and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. Merge sort divides a list in half, sorts each half, then merges them back together - it is much faster for large lists. Understanding how algorithms work helps us write better programs and choose the right approach for each problem.",
  "Network technologies": "A network is a collection of devices connected together so they can share data. Local Area Networks (LANs) connect devices in a small area like a home or office. Wide Area Networks (WANs) connect devices across large distances, often using the internet. Data travels across networks in small chunks called packets. Each device on a network has a unique MAC address (physical address) and an IP address (logical address). Routers direct packets from one network to another, while switches connect devices within a network.",
  "The internet": "The internet is a global network of networks that allows billions of devices to communicate. Data is broken into packets, each with a header containing source and destination IP addresses. Routers use routing tables to forward packets towards their destination. The TCP/IP protocol suite governs how data is transmitted - TCP ensures reliable delivery, while IP handles addressing and routing. DNS (Domain Name System) translates domain names into IP addresses. HTTP and HTTPS are the protocols used to transfer web pages.",
  "Wireless communications": "Wireless communication sends data through the air using radio waves instead of physical cables. WiFi uses radio waves to connect devices to a local network, typically within about 100 metres. Bluetooth is designed for short-range connections between personal devices, usually within 10 metres. RFID uses radio waves to read data from tags - used in contactless cards and stock tracking. NFC is a very short-range version of RFID used for contactless payments. Wireless signals can be affected by walls, interference, and distance.",
  "The Internet of Things": "The Internet of Things (IoT) describes everyday physical objects that are connected to the internet and can collect and share data. Examples include smart thermostats, fitness trackers, connected fridges, and industrial sensors. IoT devices typically contain sensors, a processor, and a wireless communication module. The data collected by IoT devices can be used to automate processes, improve efficiency, or provide useful information. Security and privacy are major concerns with IoT because many devices collect personal data and may have weak security protections.",
  "Online communication": "Online communication takes many forms including email, messaging, social media, forums, and video calls. Netiquette refers to the informal rules of polite behaviour online. Cyberbullying is a serious issue where technology is used to harass or harm others. Social media platforms allow people to share content and connect, but also raise concerns about misinformation and privacy. Digital footprints are the traces of online activity that remain on servers and can affect reputation.",
  "The networked society": "Networks have transformed society by enabling instant global communication and access to vast amounts of information. The digital divide refers to the gap between those who have access to technology and those who do not, often linked to wealth, location, or age. Data protection laws such as the UK GDPR govern how personal data must be handled. Cybersecurity threats include phishing, malware, and data breaches. Society must balance the benefits of connectivity with concerns about privacy, surveillance, and digital inequality.",
  "Percentages": "A percentage expresses a number as a fraction of 100. To convert a fraction to a percentage, divide the numerator by the denominator and multiply by 100. To find a percentage of a quantity, multiply the quantity by the percentage divided by 100. Percentages are used widely in computing to express things like CPU usage, battery level, compression ratios, and accuracy scores. To increase a value by a percentage, multiply by (1 + percentage/100). To decrease, multiply by (1 - percentage/100).",
  "Exponent notation": "Exponent notation (or index notation) is a way of writing repeated multiplication compactly. For example, 2^8 means 2 multiplied by itself 8 times, which equals 256. In computing, powers of 2 appear constantly because computers use binary. A kilobyte is 2^10 = 1024 bytes and a megabyte is 2^20 bytes. Understanding exponents helps you quickly calculate storage sizes and data quantities. The rules of exponents include: multiplying means adding exponents, dividing means subtracting exponents.",
  "Scientific notation": "Scientific notation expresses very large or very small numbers as a number between 1 and 10 multiplied by a power of 10. For example, 3,500,000 = 3.5 x 10^6. It is used to describe things like processor speeds (GHz = 10^9 Hz) and internet speeds. The exponent tells you how many places to move the decimal point - positive means larger, negative means smaller. Scientific notation makes it much easier to compare and calculate with extreme values.",
  "Binary and number systems": "Binary is a base-2 number system that uses only 0 and 1. Computers use binary because electronic circuits can easily represent two states: on and off. To convert decimal to binary, repeatedly divide by 2 and record remainders from bottom to top. To convert binary to decimal, multiply each bit by its place value (1, 2, 4, 8, 16...) and add the results. Hexadecimal (base-16) uses digits 0-9 and letters A-F. Each hex digit represents exactly 4 binary bits (a nibble). One byte is 8 bits and can store values from 0 to 255 in binary.",
  "Equations and substitution": "An equation states that two expressions are equal, and we can solve it to find an unknown value. Substitution means replacing a variable with its known value to calculate a result. For example, if speed = distance / time, and distance = 100 and time = 4, then speed = 100/4 = 25. Rearranging equations allows us to find any variable when the others are known. In computing, formulas appear in calculations for things like file sizes, transmission times, and signal strength.",
  "Inverse square law": "The inverse square law states that the intensity of something (like light, sound, or radio signals) decreases with the square of the distance from the source. If you double your distance from a WiFi router, the signal strength drops to 1/4 of what it was. This is written as I proportional to 1/d^2, where I is intensity and d is distance. The law applies to any signal that spreads outward in all directions equally. This explains why wireless networks have limited range and why signal strength weakens rapidly as you move further from an access point.",
}

